Netflix Data

1. Download the netflix_titles at this link. Create a century variable taking two values:

- '21' if the released_year is greater or equal to 2000, and

- '20' otherwise. 
library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
## Warning: package 'tidytext' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(knitr)

df <- read_csv('C:/Users/student/OneDrive - Bryant University/Desktop/Statistical_Analysis_with_R/Math421/Math421/netflix_titles.csv')

df$century <- case_when(
  df$release_year >= 2000 ~ '21',
  TRUE ~ '20'
)

2. Word Frequency

  1. Convert the description to tokens, remove all the stop words. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 20th century? Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words.
df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(type, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = '', x = 'Frequency')

  1. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 21st century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words. Plot a side-by-side bar charts to compare the most frequent words by the two centuries.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(century) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = century)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = century)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~century, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Frequency",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()

4. Sentiment Analysis

  1. Is movies/TV Shows in the 21st century tends to be more positive than those in 20th century? Use the sentiment analysis by Bing lexicons to address the question.
df %>%
    mutate(century = if_else(release_year>=2000, '21','20')) %>% 
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

  1. Do sentiment analysis using nrc and afinn lexicons. Give your comments on the results.
library(textdata)

         caption='Based on the results, it appears the 21st century had a higher
         frequency toward negative feelings, such as disgust, while the 
         20th century had a higher frequency for every other sentiment')

df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>%

    group_by(century) %>%

         sentiment results, with scores trending more toward the 
         negative side (greatest rel. freq. at sentiment = -2).
         However, based on the differences in rel. freq. at the 
         sentiment values -1 and 1, it appears the 20th century 
         had more positive sentiment overall.')

5. Modeling

  1. Use the description to predict if a movie/TV show is in 20th or 21st century. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table.
library(caret)
library(themis)
## Warning: package 'themis' was built under R version 4.2.2
library(textrecipes)
## Warning: package 'textrecipes' was built under R version 4.2.2
# Select data and set target 
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = century) %>% 
  select(target, description) 

# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df <- juice(a)

# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .7, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")
## Growing trees.. Progress: 77%. Estimated remaining time: 8 minutes, 30 seconds.
## Growing trees.. Progress: 97%. Estimated remaining time: 0 seconds.
pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.9818264
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
## Warning: package 'yardstick' was built under R version 4.2.2
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

6. Create another categorical variable from the data and do the following

- Plot side-by-side word frequency by different categories of the newly created variable

- Plot word clouds on different categories of the newly created variable

- Do sentiment analysis to compare different categories of the newly created variable

- Predict the newly created variable using the description. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. 
library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(knitr)

df <- read_csv('C:/Users/student/OneDrive - Bryant University/Desktop/Statistical_Analysis_with_R/Math421/Math421/netflix_titles.csv')

df$rating2 <- case_when(
  df$rating %in% c('G', 'PG', 'TV-G', 'TV-PG', 'TV-Y7', 'TV-Y7-FV') ~ 'family-friendly',
  df$rating %in% c('NC-17', 'PG-13', 'TV-14') ~ 'teenage_audience',
  df$rating %in% c('R', 'TV-MA') ~ 'mature_audience',
  TRUE ~ 'unrated'
)

# Side-by-side Word Frequency
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(rating2, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(rating2) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = rating2)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = rating2)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~rating2, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Frequency",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()
